{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520437"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:24:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:24:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13196"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13196"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.1,0.25,0.28,0.28]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53475"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5632"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13196"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38944"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1952"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9663"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49100"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53475"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-month history of nausea and vomiting. She vomits undigested food several hours after a meal. She has no other health issues and does not take any medications. She has been worried about her weight and put herself on an unsupervised keto diet to lose weight. Over the last three months, she managed to lose 20 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe appears cachectic and malnourished. Abdominal examination is unremarkable apart from a succussion splash. An abdominal CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2). Her serum amylase and lipase levels are within normal limits. Liver function test results are also within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Peptic ulcer disease","Carcinoma of the pancreas","Gastrointestinal lymphoma","Superior mesenteric artery syndrome","Diabetic gastroparesis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan shows a grossly dilated stomach with no flow of contents beyond the third part of the duodenum. No mass lesions are visible, either within the gut lumen or in adjacent structures. On sagittal views, the aortomesenteric angle is found to be 20\u00b0 and aortomesenteric distance is 6 mm. This narrow angle is very suggestive that the superior mesenteric artery is compressing the duodenum. This condition is typically diagnosed on radiographic imaging using criteria according to which:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is duodenal obstruction with proximal active peristalsis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe aortomesenteric angle \u226425\u00b0 and aortomesenteric distance \u22648 mm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere may be the presence of superior mesenteric artery anomalies\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuperior mesenteric artery syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as Wilkie\u0027s syndrome, is a rare disorder in which the small intestine (particularly the duodenum) or a part of it is compressed between the aorta and superior mesenteric artery. This results in chronic and partial or acute and complete gastric outlet obstruction at the level of the duodenum. Factors contributing to the narrowing of the aortomesenteric angle less than 22\u00b0 and the shortening of aortomesenteric distance between 2-8 mm result in superior mesenteric artery syndrome. Certain factors contribute to the development of the syndrome, including conditions where there is sudden loss of weight, such as malignancy, acquired immunodeficiency syndrome, burns, bariatric surgery, and anorexia nervosa. The syndrome typically presents with a combination of gastrointestinal symptoms such as nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, early satiety, and significant weight loss. Corrective surgery for scoliosis may also contribute to the condition. Knee-chest position or lying in a lateral decubitus or prone position may alleviate the symptoms by releasing tension between the aorta and superior mesenteric artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely explanation as the patient has not complained of reflux or gastritis-type symptoms. If an ulcer alone, this should either cause pain worse after eating (gastric) or better after eating (duodenal). If there is associated stricturing causing gastric outlet obstruction, this would typically occur in the distal stomach or proximal duodenum, which is not the case on this scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the pancreas\u003C/strong\u003E is an unlikely diagnosis as patients with pancreatic carcinoma typically present with jaundice and generalised pruritus due to hyperbilirubinaemia. Also, there is no mass lesion to be seen on the CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is an incorrect response because the radiographic findings favour the diagnosis of superior mesenteric artery syndrome, with no mass lesion evident and no evident extra-intestinal lymphatic involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic gastroparesis\u003C/strong\u003E is an incorrect response because it occurs secondary to diabetic neuropathy resulting in delayed gastric emptying without any significant evidence of mechanical obstruction. Nausea is the primary symptom in such patients associated with early satiety.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Superior mesenteric artery syndrome is a rare entity and should only be considered when other causes of apparent gastric outlet obstruction have been excluded."],"references":["Haider A, Sharma M, Siddiqa A. Superior mesenteric artery syndrome: A forgotten cause of duodenal obstruction. Cureus [Internet]. 2020 [cited 2023 Aug 9];12(9). Available from: https://www.cureus.com/articles/41558-superior-mesenteric-artery-syndrome-a-forgotten-cause-of-duodenal-obstruction#!/","Merrett MD, Wilson RB, Cosman P, et al. Superior Mesenteric Artery Syndrome: Diagnosis and Treatment Strategies. J Gastrointest Surg 2009; 13:287\u201392. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18810558/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38944"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13196"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20432"},{"type":"media","id":"20433"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20432"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8ziXWdOOJUMCLEPsaWtml7azLYNuPK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8ziXWdOOJUMCLEPsaWtml7azLYNuPK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":355,"height":280}},{"type":"media","id":"20433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20433"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.eme